The generalist vs. specialist tension is a rich topic — it shows up in careers, biology, organizations, medicine, AI, and philosophy of knowledge. Here's the lay of the land:

The core trade-off

A specialist goes deep in one domain — high expertise, high value in that niche, but narrow applicability. A generalist goes broad across many domains — flexible, connective, but rarely the "best" at any one thing. The classic framing is the hedgehog vs. fox (from Isaiah Berlin, borrowed from an old Greek fragment): the hedgehog knows one big thing, the fox knows many things.

Where specialists win

Complex, high-stakes narrow problems (brain surgery, tax law, quantum physics)
Stable environments where depth compounds over time
When the problem is well-defined — you know what you need
Where generalists win

Fast-changing, ambiguous environments — you don't know which skill you'll need
Problems that cross domains (most real-world problems)
Leadership, strategy, communication — roles that require integrating many inputs
Early-stage situations where versatility beats optimization
The deeper tension

It's not just practical — it's almost philosophical. Specialists risk local optimization: being excellent at something that becomes irrelevant, or missing the forest for the trees. Generalists risk superficiality: knowing a little about everything but mastering nothing, unable to go deep when depth is needed.

There's also a time dimension — many people advocate for being a generalist first (build range, explore), then specializing. Others argue the opposite: specialize early to build real credibility, then broaden. David Epstein's book Range makes a strong case for generalism; the deliberate practice literature (Ericsson, Gladwell's 10,000 hours) leans specialist.

It also shows up in:

Biology — generalist species (raccoons, humans) survive environmental shifts; specialists (pandas, koalas) are fragile to change
Organizations — T-shaped people (deep in one area, broad enough to collaborate) as a synthesis
Medicine — GPs vs. specialists, and the real problem of nobody owning the whole patient
AI — narrow AI vs. general AI is essentially this debate at a civilizational scale
