Yes — this is a really important and underappreciated point. Let me build on it.

The Classical Education model

The Trivium (grammar, logic, rhetoric) and Quadrivium (arithmetic, geometry, music, astronomy) weren't just a curriculum — they were a theory of mind. The idea was: before you can think well about anything specific, you need to learn how to think, how to reason, how to communicate. That's the foundation. Then the quadrivium applied that reasoning capacity to increasingly abstract domains.

It's explicitly generalist-first. And it produced people like:

Einstein — deeply read in philosophy (Kant, Hume, Mach), played violin seriously, thought in images and metaphors before equations
Leonardo da Vinci — the archetype, where art and anatomy and engineering were one inquiry
Leibniz — philosopher, mathematician, diplomat, historian
Newton — physicist yes, but also theologian, alchemist, obsessive reader across everything
These weren't generalists instead of specialists. They were generalists whose specialization was supercharged by breadth.

The key insight you're pointing at

Specialization without a broad foundation produces what you might call "narrow competence" — you can execute within a known framework, but you can't:

Question the framework itself
Borrow solutions from adjacent fields
Know when your specialty is the wrong tool
Communicate your ideas to the world (rhetoric)
Think about the ethics and meaning of what you're doing
Einstein didn't just solve physics problems. He asked philosophical questions about the nature of space, time, and observation — and that's precisely what led to relativity. That kind of question comes from breadth.

The modern problem

Modern education essentially inverted the classical model. You specialize earlier and earlier — pick a major, pick a track, optimize for a credential. The result is what some call "educated incapacity" — people who are highly trained but can't think outside their lane.

There's also something lost at the character level. The classical model wasn't just about knowledge — it was about forming a certain kind of person. Curious, articulate, morally reasoning, able to engage with the great questions. A specialist factory doesn't produce that.

So the thesis crystallizing here is something like:

Genuine specialization requires generalism as its prerequisite. The foundation makes the peak possible — and higher.

