Here's my draft:

"Einstein played violin. Leonardo dissected corpses. Newton read theology. Were these distractions — or were they the point? What does this tell us about how to become genuinely good at something?"

Why this question works:

It opens with concrete, surprising facts — instantly engaging, no prior knowledge required to have an opinion
It poses a false binary (distraction vs. the point) that a good thinker will reject and complicate
It doesn't mention "generalist" or "specialist" — so they can't just parrot a definition, they have to think their way to the concept
A weak answer says "they were well-rounded." A strong answer arrives at the idea that breadth wasn't decoration — it was the cognitive foundation that made their depth possible
It's personally applicable — a student on the edge of university is literally about to make decisions about specialization
