No, we didn't — and that's a really important counterpart to the thesis. It makes the whole idea symmetrical and much more interesting.

So the full picture is:

Generalism makes you a better specialist. And specialization makes you a better generalist.

They feed each other in both directions. When you go deep on something — really deep — you learn things that transfer everywhere:

You learn what rigor actually feels like — so you can smell its absence in other fields
You learn how hard mastery is — which gives you humility and calibration when you venture into new territory
You learn a domain's deep structure — and deep structures often rhyme across fields (optimization problems in economics look like natural selection in biology look like gradient descent in ML)
You learn how to learn hard things — the meta-skill transfers
So a person who has never gone deep on anything is actually a poor generalist too — they're just a dilettante. Breadth without any depth is as crippling as depth without any breadth.

The ideal the classical model was pointing at is sometimes called the "T-shaped person" in modern language — broad across the top, deep in at least one place. But the classical framing is richer: it's not a static shape, it's a dynamic back-and-forth between depth and breadth that compounds over a lifetime.

